definitions.definition: A lucky or improbable occurrence that could probably never be repeated.
examples: We've classified by a fluke ; actually, the first goal was just a total fluke .

main_definition: A lucky or improbable occurrence that could probably never be repeated.

definitions.definition: A trematode ; a parasitic flatworm of the class Trematoda , related to tapeworms (class Cestoda ).
examples: The man became infected with flukes after eating a meal of raw fish.

secondary_definitions: A trematode ; a parasitic flatworm of the class Trematoda , related to tapeworms (class Cestoda ).

definitions.definition: Any of the triangular blades at the end of an anchor , designed to catch the ground.
examples: The fluke of the anchor was wedged between two outcroppings of rock and could not be dislodged.

definitions.definition: Either of the two lobes of a whale 's or similar creature's tail .
examples: The dolphin had an open wound on the left fluke of its tail where the propeller had injured it.

definitions.definition: A metal hook on the head of certain staff weapons (such as a bill ), made in various forms depending on function, whether used for grappling or to penetrate armour when swung at an opponent.
examples: The polearm had a wide, sharpened fluke attached to the central point.

definitions.definition: In general, a winglike formation on a central piece.
examples: After casting the bronze statue, we filed down the flukes and spurs from the molding process.

main_definition: ( nautical ) Any of the triangular blades at the end of an anchor , designed to catch the ground.
secondary_definitions: Either of the two lobes of a whale 's or similar creature's tail .
A metal hook on the head of certain staff weapons (such as a bill ), made in various forms depending on function, whether used for grappling or to penetrate armour when swung at an opponent.
In general, a winglike formation on a central piece.
